A Hash Table is an implementation of a Map data structure in which each key is hashed to produce its corresponding value. The key and value are stored together in the same array, so that finding a particular key can be done by performing a binary search on the array.

The main advantage of using a Hash Table over other map implementations such as linked lists or trees is that it provides constant-time access to any given key/value pair. This makes it well-suited for use in situations where lookups must be performed frequently (such as in a database or web application), or where memory usage needs to be minimized. Additionally, since the key and value are stored together in the same array, they can easily be updated once the entry is removed from the map.

Here's an example implementation in Rust:
```rust
struct Node {
    key: u32,
    value: i64,
}

impl HashTable<u32, i64> {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Self::with_capacity(INITIAL_CAPACITY)
    }

    fn get(&self, key: &u32) -> Option<i64> {
        if let Some((index, node)) = self.binary_search(key)? {
            return Some(node.value);
        } else {
            None
        }
    }

    fn set(&mut self, key: u32, value: i64) {
        self.entry(key).and_then(|e| e.set(value));
    }

    fn remove(&mut self, key: u32) {
        self.entry(key).map(|e| e.remove());
    }

    fn contains(&self, key: u32) -> bool {
        self.binary_search(key)?.is_some()
    }

    fn size(&self) -> usize {
        self.size_in_bytes().unwrap_or(0)
    }

    fn capacity(&self) -> usize {
        self.capacities.len() as usize + 1
    }

    fn merge(&mut self, mut other: HashTable<u32, i64>) {
        other.for_each(|e| self.set(e.key, e.value));
    }

    fn clear(&mut self) {
        self.clear_in_place();
    }

    fn clear_in_place(&mut self) {
        while!self.isEmpty() {
            let key = self.keys.pop();
            self.values[key] = 0;
        }
    }

    fn keys(&self) -> Vec<_> {
        self.keys.into_iter().collect()
    }

    fn values(&self) -> Vec<_> {
        self.values.into_iter().collect()
    }
}
```
